        <trans-unit id="102" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Margin and Padding in Windows Forms Controls</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Precise placement of controls on your form is a high priority for many applications.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> namespace gives you many layout features to accomplish this.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Two of the most important are the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Margin%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Padding%2A&gt;</ph> properties.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Margin%2A&gt;</ph> property defines the space around the control that keeps other controls a specified distance from the control's borders.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Padding%2A&gt;</ph> property defines the space in the interior of a control that keeps the control's content (for example, the value of its <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Text%2A&gt;</ph> property) a specified distance from the control's borders.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following illustration shows the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Padding%2A&gt;</ph> and <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Forms.Control.Margin%2A&gt;</ph> properties on a control.</source>
        </trans-unit>
